"1600","1611":"1611","1699":"1699","1588":"1588","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","about 1611":"circa 1611","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","20 Feb 1609":"20 februari 1609","1609":"1609","1 August 1585":"1 augustus 1585","1625":"1625","Framlingham, Suffolk, England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, England","Parham, Sussex, England":"Parham, Sussex, England","Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England":"Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England","Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England":"Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1 August 1585–1681":"1 August 1585–1681","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1588–1625":"1588–1625","1609–1699":"1609–1699","1611–Male":"1611–Deceased","1565–1620":"1565–1620","1560–Female":"1560–Deceased","October 1625":"October 1625","1681":"1681","1560":"1560","18 December 1607":"18 December 1607","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1699":"1699","1588":"1588","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","about 1611":"about 1611","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","20 Feb 1609":"20 February 1609","1609":"1609","1 August 1585":"1 August 1585","1625":"1625","Framlingham, Suffolk, England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, England","Parham, Sussex, England":"Parham, Sussex, England","Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England":"Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England","Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England":"Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baylie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Bailey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailey","meanings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705208,"age":1,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":14,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":34,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":56,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Francis Baylie was born on 1 August 1585, in Parham, Sussex, England, his father, Francis Baylie, was 21 and his mother, Agnes Balie, was 26. He married Dorothy Rossell on 18 December 1607, in Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1681, in Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1 August 1585–1681":"1. august 1585–1681","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1588–1625":"1588–1625","1609–1699":"1609–1699","1611–Male":"1611–Surnud","1565–1620":"1565–1620","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","October 1625":"oktoober 1625","1681":"1681","1560":"1560","18 December 1607":"18. detsember 1607","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1699":"1699","1588":"1588","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","about 1611":"umbes 1611","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","20 Feb 1609":"20. veebruar 1609","1609":"1609","1 August 1585":"1. august 1585","1625":"1625","Framlingham, Suffolk, England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, England","Parham, Sussex, England":"Parham, Sussex, England","Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England":"Newark-on-Trent, Nottinghamshire, England","Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England":"Rothersthorpe, Northamptonshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1 August 1585–1681":"1. elokuuta 1585–1681","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1588–1625":"1588–1625","1609–1699":"1609–1699","1611–Male":"1611–Kuollut","1565–1620":"1565–1620","1560–Female":"1560–Kuollut","October 1625":"lokakuu 1625","1681":"1681","1560":"1560","18 December 1607":"18. joulukuuta 1607","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1699":"1699","1588":"1588","1620":"1620","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","about 1611":"noin 1611","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","20 Feb 1609":"20. helmikuuta 1609","1609":"1609","1 August 1585":"1. elokuuta 1585","1625":"1625","Framlingham, Suffolk, England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, England","Parham, Sussex, England":"Parham, Sussex, England","Newark-on-Trent, N